observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the General Service Officer to perform the following:
Coordinate with the DRRMO and RHU and prepare utilization reports and inventory balance for welfare goods for distribution and drugs and medicines. Furnish copy to the Accounting Office for appropriate adjustments to be made;
Maintain updated stock cards for each inventory item to ensure accurate tracking and record-keeping;
Use Requisition and Issuance Slips (RIS) when issuing inventory supplies within their respective departments; and
Consolidate the RIS into a Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the SSMI to the Accounting Office.
Direct the Municipal Accountant to perform the following:
Maintain updated supplies ledger cards for each inventory item to ensure accurate tracking and record-keeping;
Record all inventory purchases as assets in the books of accounts, in accordance with the Perpetual Inventory Method as required under Section 51 of the NGAS Manual; and
Recognize inventory supplies expense using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI).

5.6. 	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Human Resources and Management Officer to undertake the following:
Review the paid leave credits monetization in CY 2024 and make adjustments, if applicable, to first apply the monetized leave credits from available vacation leave of concerned employees;
Ensure that employees monetize first their earned VL credits before applying for monetization of the earned SL balances;
Make sure that monetization of 50% or more of accumulated VL and SL credits may be allowed only for valid and justifiable reasons, subject to the discretion of the agency head and the availability of funds;
Check and review the correctness of earned leave credits and deductions made in the Leave Ledger Cards at the end of the year to ensure accuracy of the leave credit balance of each employee;
Strictly comply with the provisions of CSC Omnibus Rules on Leave, particularly Sections 22 and 23 thereof.

We recommended to the Management the following:

Require the HRMO Officer to post and fill out the vacant position of the Municipal Assessor, as prescribed in Sections 443 and 472 of RA 7160 and in accordance with existing guidelines, rules and regulations of the Civil Service Commission, for more effective administration of the Municipal Assessor to ensure the optimal benefits to the constituents;

If already installed in the position, require the Municipal Assessor to furnish the Municipal Treasurer with the complete assessment roll as the basis for the collection of RPT and SET and for updating the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR)/ Real Property Tax Index Card (RPTIC);

Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the necessary report to the Accounting Office at the end of the year to enable the Municipal Accountant to recognize the correct amount of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts at the beginning of the year;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the amount of delinquent taxes is incorporated in the established receivable amount to be forwarded to the Municipal Accountant;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records and to make the appropriate adjustments to reflect the correct balances; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the procedures provided under the NGAS Manual for LGUs in the accounting of RPT/SET.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the GAD Focal Person to implement the following measures in compliance with Section 36 (C), Chapter VI of the IRR of RA No. 9710 and Section 4.1.B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01:
a. Gather and process sex-disaggregated data and GAD-related information from its identified sex disaggregated data sources as identified in its GAD Code;
b. Consolidate the same for data processing, data analysis and updating and maintenance of their GAD databases;
c. Institutionalize the GAD Database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, budgeting, programming, and policy formulation;
d. Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the programs, projects and activities of the GAD are responsive to the said issues.

