Recommendation:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the General Services Officer to submit the complete Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RCPPE) on or before January 31 of each year, copy furnished the COA Auditor concerned;
Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain Property Cards for each category of PPE accounts to substantiate the existence, completeness, and reliability of items composing the respective PPE accounts;
Require the General Services Officer to submit Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to the Office of the Auditor and regularly check the condition of the property and equipment. Any damage, obsolete and unserviceable property shall be reported in the IIRUP and immediately request for disposal;
Create an Appraisal Committee to evaluate the unserviceable properties, comply with the documents required, and recommend the applicable mode of disposal of the items in a Disposal Committee Resolution for the LCE’s approval and submit it to the Auditor concerned for evaluation and action thereon prior to the disposal of unserviceable items;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the obsolete, non-functional, and those no longer used in the operation as shown in IIRUP if there’s any, from their respective asset account to Other Asset Account;
Direct the General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to regularly reconcile their inventory records and review the composition of the PPE account to come up with an accurate classification of Property, Plant, and Equipment account balance; and
Direct the General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to refer to COA Circular No. 2020-006 prescribing the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of property, plant and equipment, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of Government Agencies for proper planning and its corresponding implementation.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the General Services Office to submit the Inventory Report on the Physical Count of Inventories for December 31, 2021, and observe timely submission thereafter;
Require the Municipal Accountant’s Office to coordinate with the General Services Office and reconcile their records to ascertain the reliability and validity of the balances of inventory accounts reflected in the financial statements;
Direct the General Services Office to:
Remind all departments of the LGU to prepare and submit regularly the necessary SSMIs with the original copy of the RIS to GSO for proper consolidation and timely submission to the Accounting Department; and
Maintain accurate and updated property records for each type of supplies by having Stock Cards per stock number. Difference between the balance per stock cards and per inventory count must be investigated and cleared immediately;
Direct the Municipal Accountant’s Office to maintain updated perpetual inventory records comprising of Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) for each commodity/stock and properly observe the provisions for recording of inventories and the corresponding recognition as an expense through preparation of JEV using appropriate expenditure accounts;
Create a committee to validate and certify the existence and/or issuance of the inventory items that are in the possession of the Municipal Government but are not recorded in the books of accounts, and submit a corresponding report thereon to support the recognition of the inventory items in the books of accounts; and
Remind all departments of their accountability, responsibility and liability for handling government property and inventories, and direct them to maintain and submit records/reports of their respective monthly inventory balances reflecting actual receipts and issuances for a more efficient reconciliation, inventory taking and other supply management procedures.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the concerned Municipality personnel, in coordination with the BAC, to meticulously and judiciously plan the Municipality’s Annual Procurement to avoid inconvenience and significant delays of the implementation of the Municipality’s Project, Program and Activities thereby improving the Municipality government’s delivery of public service;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to fully utilize the PhilGEPS via posting the necessary Invitation to Bid, Notice of Award, Perfected Contract and Notice to Proceed for each of the Municipality’s procurement to promote transparency and efficiency;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to meet its function and responsibility as the main support unit of the BAC for efficient processing of the Municipality’s procurement;
Direct the BAC not to resort to Alternative Mode of Procurement in the absence of conditions provided in 2016 RIRR of RA 9184 that would justify employing such mode of procurement;
Direct the BAC to stop implementation of Infrastructure Projects by Administration when the requirements set forth in the RIRR were not met;
Direct the Technical Working Group to properly evaluate the financial, technical and legal capability of the bidders to provide the HOPE with an appropriate recommendation of determining a qualified supplier, contractor or consultant;
Direct the BAC to properly and completely fill out the documents related to procurements and to avoid tampering of such to shed out doubt as to authenticity of the said documents; and
Direct the BAC and all the Municipality personnel to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA 9184 and its 2016 IRR for the Municipality to meet the principles of transparency, accountability, equity, efficiency and economy in its procurement process.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Reconsider staffing in the Municipal Accountant’s Office for additional manpower to enable them to cope up with the numerous tasks entrusted to them;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit to our office the reports not yet submitted as of to date;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to religiously comply with the prescribed period of the submission of the required reports and its supporting documents as prescribed in the COA rules and regulations.

We have recommended to the management for executive action:
Submit the resolution creating the Solid Waste Management Board;
Prepare, review and update the plan as required by law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness;
Collaborate campaign with the barangay officials concerned; 
Implement strictly the waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules;
Convert the open dump site to a controlled one.

